n Victorian material culture and political theory. It seeks to transform understanding of Victorian liberalism’s key conceptual metaphor − that the mind of an individuated subject is private space. Focusing on the environments inhabited by four Victorian writers and intellectuals, it delineates how John Stuart Mill’s, Matthew Arnold’s, John Morley’s, and Robert Browning’s commitments to liberalism were shaped by or manifested through the physical spaces in which they worked. The book also asserts the centrality of the embodied experience of actual people to Victorian political thought. Readers will gain new historical and literary understanding and will be introduced to an innovative methodology that links material culture and political theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMaterial culturezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitics and culturezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831107804370 cprintz978147443153840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781474431668?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474431668423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474431668/original  a978-3-11-078043-7  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK